 grows the black CuO \cite{Filipic2012}.  The solution's temperature is maintained between 95\,$^\circ$C and 100\,$^\circ$C during the blackening process.  Thermal and concentration gradients are minimized by using a magnetic stir bar in the blackening solution.  Immersing the beaker holding the blackening solution in a heated outer water bath also reduces thermal gradients.  The outer bath is saturated with NaCl to allow its temperature to exceed 100\,$^\circ$C without boiling and potentially contaminating the solution.

